  <!-- SECTION 2: NATIONAL CULTURE COMPARE -->
  <div class="section" id="s2">
    <div class="section-header">
      <p class="section-number">02 / 05 ¬∑ National Cultures</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Canada vs the USA ‚Äî The Big Picture</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Two countries that speak the same language, share a continent, and yet have profoundly different values, systems, and identities. Let's go dimension by dimension.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-block">

      <div class="tab-row">
        <button class="tab-btn active" onclick="showTab('identity')">Identity</button>
        <button class="tab-btn" onclick="showTab('politics')">Politics & Society</button>
        <button class="tab-btn" onclick="showTab('work')">Work Culture</button>
        <button class="tab-btn" onclick="showTab('language')">Language & Tone</button>
      </div>

      <div id="tab-identity">
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div class="compare-col canada">
            <div class="compare-flag">üçÅ</div>
            <h3>Canada ‚Äî "The Mosaic"</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>National identity is built on <strong>celebrating difference</strong> ‚Äî multiculturalism is official government policy since 1971</li>
              <li>The goal is a <strong>cultural mosaic</strong>: newcomers keep their language and traditions</li>
              <li>"Canadian-ness" is often defined by what it is <em>not</em> ‚Äî not American, not British ‚Äî rather than one dominant narrative</li>
              <li>Strong sense of collective responsibility: healthcare, education, social safety net</li>
              <li>National pride is quieter, less performative ‚Äî but deeply felt</li>
              <li>The concept of "peace, order, and good government" vs the American "life, liberty, pursuit of happiness"</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-divider">vs</div>
          <div class="compare-col usa">
            <div class="compare-flag">üá∫üá∏</div>
            <h3>USA ‚Äî "The Melting Pot"</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>The <strong>American Dream</strong>: individual effort leads to success regardless of origin</li>
              <li>The ideal is <strong>assimilation</strong>: different backgrounds blend into one shared American identity</li>
              <li>National identity is strongly and loudly expressed ‚Äî flags, pledges, patriotic rituals</li>
              <li>Individual rights and freedoms are paramount ‚Äî government interference is viewed skeptically</li>
              <li>Exceptionalism: the belief that America is uniquely great with a global mission</li>
              <li>Entrepreneurship, competition, and self-reliance are core virtues</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fun-fact">
          <div class="ff-icon">üß†</div>
          <p><strong>Leadership reflection:</strong> Think about your own organisation. Is it more of a "mosaic" (celebrating individual differences) or a "melting pot" (building a shared culture)? Which approach works better ‚Äî and when?</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div id="tab-politics" style="display:none">
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div class="compare-col canada">
            <div class="compare-flag">üçÅ</div>
            <h3>Canada ‚Äî Consensus & Care</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>Parliamentary democracy headed by a <strong>Prime Minister</strong></li>
              <li>Five major political parties ‚Äî a much broader political spectrum</li>
              <li>Universal healthcare is not a debate ‚Äî it's a <strong>national identity marker</strong></li>
              <li>Relatively low political polarisation ‚Äî 70% of Canadians are satisfied with their democracy</li>
              <li>Trust in government and institutions is high and doesn't swing dramatically by election</li>
              <li>Gun ownership is regulated; gun culture is not a defining cultural battle</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-divider">vs</div>
          <div class="compare-col usa">
            <div class="compare-flag">üá∫üá∏</div>
            <h3>USA ‚Äî Freedom & Fracture</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>Presidential republic with a powerful <strong>two-party system</strong> (Democrat vs Republican)</li>
              <li>Deeply polarised ‚Äî political opponents are often seen as enemies, not rivals</li>
              <li>Healthcare, gun rights, abortion are existential culture-war battlegrounds</li>
              <li>Only ~28% of Americans think the country is going in the right direction</li>
              <li>Deep distrust of government and institutions across large segments of society</li>
              <li>Religious identity plays a much stronger role in political and social life</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fun-fact">
          <div class="ff-icon">üí¨</div>
          <p><strong>Discussion:</strong> Canada is described as united despite celebrating differences; the USA aims for unity but is deeply divided. What does this tell us about the relationship between multiculturalism and social cohesion?</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div id="tab-work" style="display:none">
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div class="compare-col canada">
            <div class="compare-flag">üçÅ</div>
            <h3>Canada ‚Äî Collaborative & Balanced</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>Polite, consensus-driven communication ‚Äî building agreement before deciding</li>
              <li><strong>Team contribution</strong> is valued over individual star performance</li>
              <li>Strong employee protections ‚Äî no "at-will" employment; termination requires documented cause</li>
              <li>Mandatory paid breaks, statutory holidays, and at least 2 weeks' vacation by law</li>
              <li>Parental leave is generous and widely used by both parents</li>
              <li>After-hours disconnection is culturally normal ‚Äî Canadians are less likely to identify with their job</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-divider">vs</div>
          <div class="compare-col usa">
            <div class="compare-flag">üá∫üá∏</div>
            <h3>USA ‚Äî Driven & Direct</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>Direct, assertive communication ‚Äî "Let's cut to the chase", "What's your bottom line?"</li>
              <li><strong>Individual achievement</strong> and visibility are rewarded and expected</li>
              <li>Employment is largely "at-will" ‚Äî easier to hire and fire</li>
              <li>Fewer legal protections around holidays and vacation ‚Äî hustle culture is real</li>
              <li>Americans often strongly identify with their career and profession</li>
              <li>Networking, self-promotion, and personal branding are essential professional skills</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="fun-fact">
          <div class="ff-icon">üß†</div>
          <p><strong>Leadership angle:</strong> As future leaders, which style is more effective in today's world ‚Äî the assertive American directness or the Canadian consensus-building approach? Can they be combined? When would you choose one over the other?</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div id="tab-language" style="display:none">
        <div class="compare-grid">
          <div class="compare-col canada">
            <div class="compare-flag">üçÅ</div>
            <h3>Canada ‚Äî Softened & Bilingual</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>Officially bilingual: English <em>and</em> French ‚Äî shaped by a bicultural founding</li>
              <li>Communication is softer ‚Äî "Sorry, but‚Ä¶", "Would you mind if‚Ä¶?" are default openers</li>
              <li>Canadian spelling blends British and American: <em>colour, centre, favourite</em></li>
              <li>"Eh?" functions as a social invitation ‚Äî checking for agreement, keeping conversation open</li>
              <li>Over <strong>160 languages</strong> spoken in Toronto alone; multilingualism is the norm</li>
              <li>Politeness on social media ‚Äî Canadian Twitter was found to be measurably more civil than American Twitter in studies</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-divider">vs</div>
          <div class="compare-col usa">
            <div class="compare-flag">üá∫üá∏</div>
            <h3>USA ‚Äî Casual & Confident</h3>
            <ul class="compare-items">
              <li>English-only as de facto standard, though Spanish is widely spoken</li>
              <li>Communication is casual and direct even with strangers or in business: "Hi!" vs "Good morning"</li>
              <li>American English spelling is the global pop-culture default: <em>color, center, favorite</em></li>
              <li>Filler phrases lean toward affirmation: "Awesome!", "Absolutely!", "For sure!"</li>
              <li>NYC alone hosts speakers of <strong>~800 languages</strong> ‚Äî the most linguistically diverse city on Earth</li>
              <li>American slang spreads globally through film, TV, and social media far faster than Canadian equivalents</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
