  <!-- SECTION 4: HOFSTEDE + LEADERSHIP -->
  <div class="section" id="s4">
    <div class="section-header">
      <p class="section-number">04 / 05 ¬∑ Leadership Lens</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Cultural Dimensions for Leaders</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Using frameworks from cultural psychology, let's see where Canada and the USA actually sit ‚Äî and what that means for how you lead across borders.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-block">

      <div class="dimension-card">
        <div class="dim-header">
          <div>
            <div class="dim-title">Individualism vs Collectivism</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--warm-gray);margin-top:4px;">How much do people prioritise personal goals vs group harmony?</div>
          </div>
          <div class="dim-emoji">üë§</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dim-spectrum">
          <div class="spectrum-labels"><span class="ca-label">Canada ‚Äî High Individualism (but with guardrails)</span><span class="us-label">USA ‚Äî Extreme Individualism</span></div>
          <div class="spectrum-bar">
            <div class="spectrum-marker ca" title="Canada">üçÅ</div>
            <div class="spectrum-marker us" title="USA">üá∫üá∏</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="dim-desc">Both countries are individualist ‚Äî but the USA scores among the highest in the world (91/100), while Canada (80/100) is more comfortable with collective solutions like public healthcare. In Canada, individual ambition is tempered by a "we're all in this together" spirit. In the USA, the individual hero narrative is dominant. <strong>For leaders visiting Toronto:</strong> Expect collaboration and consensus-seeking ‚Äî but don't mistake politeness for passivity.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dimension-card">
        <div class="dim-header">
          <div>
            <div class="dim-title">Power Distance</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--warm-gray);margin-top:4px;">How much do people accept hierarchy and unequal power?</div>
          </div>
          <div class="dim-emoji">üëë</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dim-spectrum">
          <div class="spectrum-labels"><span class="ca-label">Canada ‚Äî Lower Power Distance</span><span class="us-label">USA ‚Äî Moderate Power Distance</span></div>
          <div class="spectrum-bar">
            <div class="spectrum-marker ca" style="left:20%">üçÅ</div>
            <div class="spectrum-marker us" style="left:40%">üá∫üá∏</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="dim-desc">Canada is relatively egalitarian ‚Äî managers and employees communicate more openly, decisions often involve input from multiple levels, and challenging authority politely is acceptable. American workplaces can be more hierarchical than they appear ‚Äî the CEO culture is strong. <strong>Practical tip:</strong> In Toronto meetings, expect juniors to speak up; don't interpret silence as disagreement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dimension-card">
        <div class="dim-header">
          <div>
            <div class="dim-title">Uncertainty Avoidance</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--warm-gray);margin-top:4px;">How comfortable are people with ambiguity and risk?</div>
          </div>
          <div class="dim-emoji">üé≤</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dim-spectrum">
          <div class="spectrum-labels"><span class="ca-label">Canada ‚Äî Moderate (comfort with ambiguity)</span><span class="us-label">USA ‚Äî Lower (risk-tolerant)</span></div>
          <div class="spectrum-bar">
            <div class="spectrum-marker ca" style="left:50%">üçÅ</div>
            <div class="spectrum-marker us" style="left:30%">üá∫üá∏</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="dim-desc">American entrepreneurial culture celebrates taking risks and failing fast ‚Äî Silicon Valley mythology. Canada is more cautious ‚Äî regulation is welcome, safety nets matter, and decisions are more measured. Interestingly, Toronto has a thriving startup scene that blends both: the ambition of the American model with more social support underneath.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dimension-card">
        <div class="dim-header">
          <div>
            <div class="dim-title">Long-Term vs Short-Term Orientation</div>
            <div style="font-size:13px;color:var(--warm-gray);margin-top:4px;">Do people plan for the future or focus on immediate results?</div>
          </div>
          <div class="dim-emoji">üî≠</div>
        </div>
        <div class="dim-spectrum">
          <div class="spectrum-labels"><span class="ca-label">Canada ‚Äî Slightly more long-term</span><span class="us-label">USA ‚Äî Shorter-term (quarterly thinking)</span></div>
          <div class="spectrum-bar">
            <div class="spectrum-marker ca" style="left:55%">üçÅ</div>
            <div class="spectrum-marker us" style="left:35%">üá∫üá∏</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="dim-desc">American business culture is famously short-termist ‚Äî quarterly earnings, shareholder returns, fast exits. Canadian business culture, while competitive, tends toward more measured, long-term relationship building. This shows up in negotiation: Canadian business partners often invest more time in building trust before the deal.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="fun-fact">
        <div class="ff-icon">üåç</div>
        <p><strong>The Dutch connection:</strong> Where does the Netherlands fit on these dimensions? You come from a low power-distance, relatively individualist culture ‚Äî which means you may find Canada's communication style more familiar than you expect. But Canada's multicultural workplace may still surprise you in other ways. What cultural adjustment will you need to make?</p>
      </div>

    </div>
    <div class="section-nav">
      <button class="nav-btn prev" onclick="goSection(3)">‚Üê Toronto vs NYC</button>
      <span class="section-progress">Section 4 of 5</span>
      <button class="nav-btn next" onclick="goSection(5)">Reflection & Takeaways ‚Üí</button>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- SECTION 5: REFLECTION -->
  <div class="section" id="s5">
    <div class="section-header">
      <p class="section-number">05 / 05 ¬∑ Reflection & Action</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What Will You Take to Toronto?</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Culture isn't just something you observe ‚Äî it's something you interact with. As future leaders, cultural intelligence is one of your most powerful assets.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="content-block">

      <div class="activity-prompt">
        <h3>üéØ Group Activity (15 minutes)</h3>
        <p style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.9); font-size:14px; margin-bottom:16px; line-height:1.7">In groups of 3-4, discuss the following questions and prepare a 90-second response to share with the class:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Based on what you've learned today, what's the <strong>one cultural difference</strong> between Canada and the USA that surprised you most ‚Äî and why?</li>
          <li>As a Dutch student going to Toronto: what cultural adjustment do you think you personally will need to make? What might come naturally to you?</li>
          <li>Imagine you're opening a startup in Toronto. Name one thing about Toronto's culture that you'd want to leverage ‚Äî and one cultural assumption from home you'd need to let go of.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <div class="reflection-grid">
        <div class="reflection-card">
          <h3>üß≠ Cultural Sensitivity Checklist</h3>
          <p>Before you arrive in Toronto, be aware of: the <em>mosaic</em> rather than melting pot dynamic, the value of genuine politeness (not small talk ‚Äî actual care), the pride Torontonians have in being distinct from NYC, the extraordinary density of cultures in every single neighbourhood, and that the city's "Canadian politeness" masks extraordinary ambition and innovation underneath.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="reflection-card">
          <h3>üîç Things to Notice On the Ground</h3>
          <p>Watch how people interact in public spaces ‚Äî on the subway, in coffee shops, in queues. Listen for the mix of languages. Notice how businesses serve multicultural communities. Pay attention to how Canadian directness <em>differs</em> from Dutch directness. Look for the Canadian flag and how differently it is displayed versus the American flag. These micro-signals reveal macro-culture.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="reflection-card">
          <h3>üöÄ The Innovation Angle</h3>
          <p>Toronto is home to Google's largest office outside the US, major AI research labs (Vector Institute, Mila), a booming fintech and medtech scene, and the MaRS Discovery District ‚Äî one of the world's largest urban innovation hubs. This isn't the shy Canada of stereotype. It's a confident, globally-connected innovation ecosystem. How does cultural openness fuel this?</p>
        </div>
        <div class="reflection-card">
          <h3>ü§ù The Leadership Takeaway</h3>
          <p>The Canadian workplace model ‚Äî collaborative, respectful of work-life balance, diversity-first ‚Äî is increasingly what modern leadership theory advocates globally. You'll see it in practice in Toronto. The question for leaders isn't "which culture is better?" ‚Äî it's "when do I need which approach?" Adaptive cultural fluency is the skill to build.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="takeaway-row">
        <div class="takeaway-item">
          <div class="icon">ü™û</div>
          <p><strong>See yourself clearly</strong><br>Understand your own cultural defaults before judging others'</p>
        </div>
        <div class="takeaway-item">
          <div class="icon">üß©</div>
          <p><strong>Embrace the mosaic</strong><br>Not every culture needs to merge ‚Äî difference can be a strength</p>
        </div>
        <div class="takeaway-item">
          <div class="icon">üîä</div>
          <p><strong>Listen beyond words</strong><br>Cultural communication is about what's <em>not</em> said as much as what is</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="fun-fact" style="margin-top:32px; background:rgba(200,169,81,0.15); border:1px solid var(--gold);">
        <div class="ff-icon">‚úàÔ∏è</div>
        <p style="color:var(--cream)"><strong>Safe travels ‚Äî and enjoy Toronto!</strong> Go in curious, go in humble, go in open. The best cultural learning happens not in the classroom but when you're eating jerk chicken in Scarborough, watching the sun set over Lake Ontario, or having an unexpectedly deep conversation with a stranger on the TTC. That's the real masterclass.</p>
      </div>

    </div>
